If you want to convert the Bootstrap interface to plain CSS for greater customization and to drop the Bootstrap dependency, you'll need to rewrite the Bootstrap classes and components in your HTML templates and replace them with your own CSS classes. Here's a minimal example showing how you can redesign the participants interface with plain CSS.

First, let's start by setting up a basic style for your page in the `style.css` file:

```css
/* crm_app/static/css/style.css */
body {
    font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif;
    background-color: #f8f9fa;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    color: #333;
}

.container {
    width: 80%;
    margin: 20px auto;
}

.btn {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: 10px 20px;
    font-size: 14px;
    cursor: pointer;
    background-color: #007bff;
    color: white;
    border: 1px solid #007bff;
    border-radius: 3px;
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: background-color 0.2s;
}

.btn:hover {
    background-color: #0056b3;
}

.btn-primary {
    background-color: #007bff;
    border: 1px solid #007bff;
}

.form-group {
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
}

.form-control {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    padding: 0.375rem 0.75rem;
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: #495057;
    background-color: #fff;
    background-clip: padding-box;
    border: 1px solid #ced4da;
    border-radius: 0.25rem;
    transition: border-color 0.15s ease-in-out, box-shadow 0.15s ease-in-out;
}

.form-control:focus {
    border-color: #80bdff;
    outline: 0;
    box-shadow: 0 0 0 0.2rem rgba(0,123,255,.25);
}

.list-group {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin-top: 20px;
}

.list-group-item {
    background-color: #fff;
    border: 1px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, .125);
    border-radius: 0.25rem;
    padding: 0.75rem 1.25rem;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
}

hr {
    margin-top: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    border: 0;
    border-top: 1px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
}

.header {
    background-color: #007bff;
    color: white;
    padding: 10px 0;
    text-align: center;
}

nav ul {
    list-style-type: none;
    overflow: hidden;
    background-color: #343a40;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
}

nav li {
    float: left;
}

nav li a {
    display: block;
    color: white;
    text-align: center;
    padding: 14px 16px;
    text-decoration: none;
}

nav li a:hover {
    background-color: #007bff;
}
```

Then update the `base.html` and other related templates to use these classes instead.

```html
<!-- crm_app/templates/base.html -->
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>CRM System</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="{{ url_for('static', filename='css/style.css') }}">
</head>
<body>
    <div class="header">
        <h1>CRM System</h1>
    </div>
    <nav>
        <ul>
            <li><a href="{{ url_for('participant_bp.view_participants') }}">Participants</a></li>
            <li><a href="{{ url_for('group_bp.view_groups') }}">Groups</a></li>
        </ul>
    </nav>
    <div class="container">
        {% block content %}
        {% endblock %}
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

Make sure you update `participants.html` and `groups.html` to replace Bootstrap classes with your own.

This `style.css` file is a starting point and will style your CRM system similar to the Bootstrap version. However, the styles are quite basic and will require expansion to cover all elements and states you want to style.

Lastly, ensure you adjust your HTML templates to fit the new CSS styles accordingly. The above example covers the conversion from Bootstrap classes to ones defined in your own CSS file, but this is a basic example. You might need to add more styles based upon your design requirements. Remember to remove any Bootstrap references from your HTML templates.

CSS code should be written in a `.css` file that is typically located within the `static` directory of your Flask project. This way, your CSS files can be served efficiently by Flask as static files when requested by the client's browser. Within the `crm_app` project structure outlined in previous responses, the CSS file should be:

```
/crm_app/
    /static/
        /css/
            style.css
```

Here's some sample code for the `style.css` file. This code will set up very basic styling for the CRM application. Depending on your specific UI/UX design requirements, you'd extend this with your custom styles.

File: `crm_app/static/css/style.css`

```css
/* Reset some basic elements */
body, h1, h2, h3, p {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
}

/* Set the font for the entire body */
body {
    font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif;
    line-height: 1.6;
    padding: 20px;
    background-color: #f4f4f4;
}

/* The .container class will center and contain the content */
.container {
    width: 80%;
    margin: auto;
    overflow: hidden;
}

/* Style for header */
header {
    background: #333;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 20px;
    text-align: center;
}

/* Style for navigation bar */
nav {
    background: #555;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 15px;
    text-align: center;
}

nav a {
    color: #fff;
    text-decoration: none;
    padding: 0 20px;
}

nav a:hover {
    background: #333;
}

/* Apply styles to forms and buttons */
input[type='text'],
input[type='email'],
input[type='submit'] {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    padding: 10px;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
}

input[type='submit'] {
    background: #333;
    color: #fff;
    cursor: pointer;
}

input[type='submit']:hover {
    background: #555;
}

/* Table styles for participant/group list */
table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    margin-top: 20px;
}

table, th, td {
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    padding: 10px;
    text-align: left;
}

/* Footer styling */
footer {
    background: #333;
    color: #fff;
    text-align: center;
    padding: 10px;
    position: absolute;
    bottom: 0;
    width: 100%;
}

/* Utility classes */
.hidden {
    display: none;
}

.text-center {
    text-align: center;
}
```

You can link this CSS file within your HTML templates by referencing it in the `<head>` section of your base template (`base.html`). Flask provides a helper function `url_for` to generate URL for the static files.

Add this line in the head of your `crm_app/templates/base.html`:

```html
<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="{{ url_for('static', filename='css/style.css') }}">
```

This line of code creates a link element in your HTML which tells the browser to load and apply the CSS styles from the specified file. The `url_for` function is used here to generate the correct URL for static files, considering the application's root path and static file settings.

Any time you make changes to your `style.css`, the changes will apply to all the HTML files that extend from `base.html` (as long as they include the appropriate block content to inherit from it). Adjust and expand upon this CSS code to suit the overall design and layout you require for the CRM application.
